'''Grup d'Elx''', is one of the post-[[World War II]] artistic movement in [[Valencia]], was founded in [[Elche]]<ref name="Ajuntamiento de Elche">{{cite news |url=http://www.elche.es/micrositios/museos/info/1619/el-grup-delx/ |title=El Grup d'Elx y la fundació del MACE. |last= |first= |date=May 14, 2013 |publisher=Ajuntamiento de Elche |accessdate=2014-01-26}}</ref> in October 1967 by poet [[Vicente Aguilera Cerní]]. The [[avant-garde]] group had connections to the [[Surrealist]] and [[Social realism]] movements and stressed the importance of both the human being and its social entourage.<ref name="El País">{{cite news |url=http://elpais.com/diario/2002/12/26/cvalenciana/1040933890_850215.html |title=El Grup d'Elx regresa tras 27 años |last=Cerdán |first=David |date=December 26, 2002 |publisher=El País |accessdate=2014-01-26}}</ref>
== History == [[File:Mutand dAguila Joan Castejon Wax on Paper 1982 100x81.jpg|thumb|220px|'Mutant eagle', wax on paper, by Joan Castejon.]] The Grup d' Elx artists began their training in an precarious artistic scenario. Its activity was a task that built a bridge between modernity and vertebrate and radical vanguard, which for them was inseparable from a social transition out of the [[Francoist]] dictatorship. In this sense, as the members of El Paso or [[Dau al set]], the artists of the Grup d' Elx conducted an art in which there are several components that are part of a common denominator: primacy of intense expressiveness, intentional reduction of color to a minimum and, finally, the belief in an artistic poetics of engagement centered on human beings and their social situation. In fact, one of its most representative members, [[Joan Castejón]], was imprisoned for four years.<ref name="Así era entonces.">{{cite news |url=http://elpais.com/diario/1999/05/30/cvalenciana/928091899_850215.html |title=Así era entonces. |last=A. Máñez |first=Julio |date=May 30, 1999 |publisher=[[El País]] |accessdate=2014-01-26}}</ref><ref name="Condenado">{{cite news |url=http://elpais.com/diario/1999/02/15/cvalenciana/919109899_850215.html |title=Condenado a tres años de dibujos forzados. |last=Cerdán Tato |first=Enrique |date=30 May 1999 |publisher=[[El País]] |accessdate=2014-01-26}}</ref>
The group was inspired by the activity of other postwar artistic groups such as [[Dau al Set]] and [[Grup Parpalló]]. Members of Grup d'Elx included [[Joan Castejón]], Albert Agulló, Antoni Coll y Sixto Marco.
The group dissolved in 1973.
==See also== *[[Joan Castejón]] *[[Dau al set]] *[[Social realism]]
